{"metadata":{"kernelspec":{"language":"python","display_name":"Python 3","name":"python3"},"language_info":{"name":"python","version":"3.12.12","mimetype":"text/x-python","codemirror_mode":{"name":"ipython","version":3},"pygments_lexer":"ipython3","nbconvert_exporter":"python","file_extension":".py"},"kaggle":{"accelerator":"none","dataSources":[{"sourceType":"datasetVersion","sourceId":16100232,"datasetId":10323252,"databundleVersionId":17071067},{"sourceType":"datasetVersion","sourceId":16054729,"datasetId":10295889,"databundleVersionId":17022235},{"sourceType":"datasetVersion","sourceId":16022163,"datasetId":10276582,"databundleVersionId":16987090},{"sourceType":"datasetVersion","sourceId":16359091,"datasetId":10486968,"databundleVersionId":17350733},{"sourceType":"datasetVersion","sourceId":16441612,"datasetId":10538231,"databundleVersionId":17439922},{"sourceType":"kernelVersion","sourceId":321931526},{"sourceType":"kernelVersion","sourceId":321971584}],"dockerImageVersionId":31328,"isInternetEnabled":true,"language":"python","sourceType":"notebook","isGpuEnabled":false}},"nbformat_minor":4,"nbformat":4,"cells":[{"source":"<a href=\"https://www.kaggle.com/code/mehulkumar99/rag-sql?scriptVersionId=322179009\" target=\"_blank\"><img align=\"left\" alt=\"Kaggle\" title=\"Open in Kaggle\" src=\"https://kaggle.com/static/images/open-in-kaggle.svg\"></a>","metadata":{},"cell_type":"markdown"},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"\n\n---\n\n## What This RAG Pipeline Does\n\n**Goal:** Fit oversized database schemas within the 2048 token limit by pruning irrelevant columns before building the prompt. Primary motivation is prompt fitting, not precision retrieval.\n\n**Pipeline in order:**\n\n**1. Schema Parsing вЂ” `parse_columns_from_augmented_schema()`**\nParses the augmented schema for a given `db_id` into a flat list of column-level dictionaries. Each dict contains `table_name`, `col_name`, `col_info` (the full augmented line with type and sample rows), `is_pk`, `is_fk`, and `chunk`. Only `col_info` is used for embedding вЂ” not the table name prefix.\n\n**2. Embedding вЂ” `create_columns_embeddings()`**\nEncodes each `col_info` string using `sentence-transformers/all-MiniLM-L6-v2` into a 384-dimensional vector. Embeddings are stored in `schema_lookup[db_id]['embeddings']` . This runs once offline вЂ” not at inference time.\n\n**3. Scoring вЂ” `scoring_columns()`**\nAt query time, embeds the question and computes cosine similarity against all column embeddings for that database. Returns a ranked list of `(score, column_dict)` pairs. PK and FK columns are then boosted to <mark>score 1.0</mark> and re-sorted вЂ” guaranteeing join columns are never pruned.\n\n**4. Compaction вЂ” `building_compact_schema()`**\nTakes the top-K scored columns and reconstructs a schema string grouped by table, preserving the original augmented format. Tables with no surviving columns are dropped entirely.\n\n**5. Adaptive Pruning вЂ” `adaptive_pruning()`**\nChecks if the full prompt <mark>exceeds 2048 tokens.</mark> If not, returns the full schema unchanged. If yes, applies an initial proportional cut using `K = floor((token_limit/length) * n_cols)`, then iteratively shrinks further in a while loop until the prompt fits.\n\n---\n\n## Known Limitations\n\n**1. Single fused embedding вЂ” no component weighting**\n`all-MiniLM-L6-v2` encodes the entire `col_info` string into one vector. The contribution of column name, data type, and sample rows cannot be separated or weighted after the fact. A short but semantically irrelevant column name can score high purely because its sample rows match words in the question.\n\n**2. Sample row contamination**\nSample rows contain real data values вЂ” city names, team names, person names. If the question mentions <mark>\"Washington Nationals,\"</mark> any column whose sample rows contain <mark>\"Washington\"</mark> scores high regardless of semantic relevance. Reducing to 1 sample row per column, or removing sample rows entirely, would reduce this noise at the cost of losing type disambiguation.\n\n**3. Table name removed from embedding вЂ” loss of context**\nEmbedding `col_info` only (without table name prefix) was a deliberate fix for table name overpowering. But for columns with non-descriptive names like <mark>sv </mark>, <mark>br </mark>, <mark>na_assoc </mark>, the embedding has almost no semantic signal вЂ” the table name was the only context. These columns get random-like similarity scores.\n\n**4. FK/PK always boosted to 1.0 regardless of relevance**\nFor databases with many tables, this guarantees irrelevant FK/PK columns always enter the top-K, consuming token budget ahead of potentially more relevant non-FK columns. For the extreme outlier database (7000+ tokens), this could cause relevant columns to be pushed out. `Accepted as a tradeoff` вЂ” join columns must not be accidentally pruned.\n\n**5. No column recall measurement**\nThe optimal retrieval strategy was never validated against a ground truth column recall metric. Gold SQL could be parsed to extract required tables and columns, and recall@K computed. The FK/PK boost score of 1.0, the number of sample rows, and the embedding strategy were all chosen by reasoning and empirical accuracy вЂ” not by directly measuring `retrieval quality`.\n\n**6. Token counting is expensive**\nToken counting inside the while loop adds <mark>1-2 tokenizer calls</mark> per over-limit example вЂ” acceptable at current scale but worth noting for production latency.\n\n---\n\n## What Would Likely Improve It\n\n**High impact:**\n- Measure column recall@K against gold SQL before optimizing anything else вЂ” gives a ground truth signal for retrieval quality\n- `Reduce sample rows` from 3 to 1, or embed column name + type only, to reduce contamination noise\n- Table-first then column retrieval вЂ” retrieve relevant tables first, then retrieve columns only within those tables. Reduces FK/PK token waste from irrelevant tables. Use `Breadth first search (BFS)` for join table discovery. \n\n**Medium impact:**\n- Separate embeddings for table name, column name, and sample rows with `weighted combination` вЂ” allows tuning relative importance of each\n- `Grid search` over weights using column recall as the metric\n- Adaptive initial top_k based on database column count rather than fixed 10\n\n**Low impact given current results:**\n- Adding 393 over-limit training examples via RAG вЂ” model already saturated on current distribution, marginal accuracy gain expected\n- Switching embedding model вЂ” `all-MiniLM-L6-v2` is small but sufficient; gains from a larger model would be modest given the contamination issues are structural\n- ","metadata":{"_kg_hide-input":false,"_kg_hide-output":true}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"\n# !pip install --upgrade torch torchvision torchaudio -q\n# !pip install --upgrade huggingface_hub -q\n# !pip install \"unsloth @ git+https://github.com/unslothai/unsloth.git\" -q\n# !pip install \"unsloth_zoo @ git+https://github.com/unslothai/unsloth-zoo.git\" --force-reinstall --no-cache-dir -q\n# !pip install --no-deps \"xformers<0.0.29\" \"trl<0.13.0\" peft accelerate bitsandbytes -q\n# !pip install -q \"numpy==2.0.2\" \n","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-05-26T03:43:11.747321Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-05-26T03:43:11.747936Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-05-26T03:43:11.752142Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-05-26T03:43:11.747901Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-05-26T03:43:11.751301Z"},"scrolled":true,"_kg_hide-output":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":1},{"cell_type":"code","source":"import os\nos.environ['LD_LIBRARY_PATH'] = '/usr/local/lib/python3.12/dist-packages/nvidia/cu13/lib:' + os.environ.get('LD_LIBRARY_PATH', '')\n\n!pip install --upgrade huggingface_hub -q\n!pip install \"torchvision>=0.27.0\" --upgrade -q\n!pip install \"unsloth @ git+https://github.com/unslothai/unsloth.git\" -q\n!pip install \"unsloth_zoo @ git+https://github.com/unsl